00:57.222 --> 01:00.558
oh, my.
That's the 11th time...

01:00.626 --> 01:03.628
I've been up and down
those stairs this morning.

01:03.696 --> 01:08.533
I don't know why you do it, ma.
I know Oscar's a guest,
but he's impossible.

01:08.600 --> 01:10.669
I can see why
he drives daddy up the wall.

01:10.736 --> 01:13.404
Oh, well,
he won't be here for long.

01:13.472 --> 01:15.807
Where is your father anyway?

01:15.875 --> 01:19.878
Oh. Oscar got up early,
came down and grabbed
Archie's sports section.

01:19.945 --> 01:22.513
He went back to bed,
so Archie had to go out
and get another paper.

01:22.581 --> 01:26.084
Oh, I bet that
made him mad.

01:26.152 --> 01:31.289
There was one other relative
that aggravated your
father-in-law like that.

01:31.356 --> 01:37.028
Kind of a tall fellow
with reddish hair.
Real large earlobes.

01:39.131 --> 01:44.936
And warts on his right hand
that he used to wear
a glove to cover.

01:45.004 --> 01:47.672
Ma, that's cousin Oscar.

01:47.740 --> 01:50.575
That's right.

01:52.144 --> 01:56.047
He just don't wear
the glove no more.

01:56.115 --> 02:00.551
Oh, Archie, there you are.
You had to get another paper?

02:00.619 --> 02:04.723
Uh, no, Edith.
I had to go out
and inspect the traffic lights.

02:04.790 --> 02:08.193
"Don't walk. Walk."
"Don't walk. Walk,"
you know?

02:08.259 --> 02:11.462
They work fine.

02:11.530 --> 02:13.698
I got something
to tell all of youse.
I made up my mind.

02:13.766 --> 02:15.967
I'm going to get rid
of that bum Oscar today.

02:16.035 --> 02:18.203
I got a call in to
cousin Lou in Detroit.

02:18.270 --> 02:21.940
He's the head of the family.
Let him figure out some way
to get Oscar home.

02:22.007 --> 02:24.575
And by the way,
where's our guest of honor
at this moment?

02:24.643 --> 02:27.645
He's in bed.
12:00 nearly,

02:27.713 --> 02:31.716
and that deadbeat
is still up there sawing wood?
Maybe he's tired.

02:31.784 --> 02:35.286
Well, I ain't surprised.
He was up half the night
flushing the toilet.

02:37.289 --> 02:39.190
That's what has me
a wreck today.

02:39.258 --> 02:44.095
Yeah, I heard that too.
Maybe the man has a problem.
Maybe he isn't well.

02:44.163 --> 02:47.665
He's well all right.
After the third flush
he was doing it to spite me.

02:49.668 --> 02:52.103
All his life
he's been spiting me.

02:52.171 --> 02:54.639
It could be insomnia.

02:54.706 --> 02:59.210
Some people listen to water
to help them fall asleep.

03:01.546 --> 03:07.285
So he was running between
his room and the toilet 32 times
to help himself go to sleep?

03:07.352 --> 03:11.489
It does sound complicated
when you think about it.

03:11.556 --> 03:14.225
Do me a favor, huh?
Just butt out
of the conversation.

03:14.293 --> 03:16.627
His whole being here
is your fault anyhow.

03:16.695 --> 03:20.698
Now will you vacate
that chair, meathead?

03:20.766 --> 03:24.769
Daddy, the man showed up
at our front door
looking so desperate.

03:24.837 --> 03:28.306
He's your cousin, Archie.
How could I say no?

03:28.373 --> 03:31.375
This way, Edith. "No."

03:33.412 --> 03:37.581
Maybe we'll all feel better
if we had breakfast now.

03:37.649 --> 03:39.818
<i>Oh, yeah. Good.</i>
<i>I'm starving.</i>
<i>Yeah, me too.</i>

03:39.885 --> 03:43.054
- Shouldn't we tell Oscar
we're eating?
- No, no, no.

03:43.122 --> 03:45.589
If he's still up there,
we'll leave him go hungry.

03:45.657 --> 03:47.591
Oh, he won't go hungry.

03:47.659 --> 03:52.864
Right after he went to bed
with your sports section, I
took him up a little something.

03:52.932 --> 03:57.768
Edith, I'm the married guy here,
and I don't get
my breakfast in bed.

03:57.837 --> 04:00.738
It was just a poached egg
and some prunes.

04:00.806 --> 04:03.541
That ain't the point
what it is, Edith.

04:03.608 --> 04:06.277
And if there's anything
that that guy don't need,
it's prunes.

04:12.151 --> 04:15.987
Geez, I'm trying to figure out
how to get rid of the guy, she's
giving him breakfast in bed.

04:16.055 --> 04:18.957
And nothing on the table
for us.
I'll get it right away.

04:19.024 --> 04:21.091
I'll help you, ma.

04:21.160 --> 04:24.295
Hey, arch, how long
you felt this way
about Oscar?

04:24.363 --> 04:26.965
Aw, forever.
He was six years older
than me.

04:27.032 --> 04:29.533
He was always
this big hump with
a whole lot of red hair...

04:29.601 --> 04:32.270
And earlobes
as big as apricots.

04:32.338 --> 04:35.173
And all kinds of warts.
When we was kids,

04:35.241 --> 04:38.776
he was always chasing me
on the grass, knocking me down
and sitting on my face.

04:40.712 --> 04:45.083
- That's it?
- Ain't that enough?

04:45.150 --> 04:48.152
You mean all he ever did
was sit on your face
on the grass?

04:48.220 --> 04:50.088
Sometimes on the cement.

04:51.556 --> 04:54.425
I can see where you can really
get to hate a guy for that.

04:54.493 --> 04:56.494
How's cousin Oscar
related to you anyway, daddy?

04:56.561 --> 05:00.564
Aw, who knows?
Like any second cousin
eight or nine times removed.

05:00.632 --> 05:03.434
Wait a minute.
I think I remember.

05:03.502 --> 05:08.006
Your sister Alma
had a brother Phil--

05:08.073 --> 05:12.911
<i>wait a minute, Edith.</i>
<i>Why do you say my sister</i>
<i>Alma had a brother Phil?</i>

05:14.446 --> 05:18.883
If my sister had
a brother Phil, then
I had a brother Phil too.

05:18.951 --> 05:23.788
Well, sure.
But it's that way
in every family, Archie.

05:26.158 --> 05:31.829
Like my sister Helen
is also my sister gertrude's--

05:31.897 --> 05:34.465
oh, stifle it, will ya?
I understand.

05:35.767 --> 05:38.002
Hey, what is this?
What's in these bottles?

05:38.070 --> 05:41.272
Oh, those are
Oscar's vitamin supplements.

05:41.340 --> 05:46.344
He don't need no supplements.
The guy eats as much
as all of us put together.

05:46.412 --> 05:48.579
If Oscar was here regular,
I'd give myself three months...

05:48.647 --> 05:51.416
Then it's over the hill
to the poor house for me.
Eggs, Archie?

05:51.483 --> 05:55.320
No, no. Forget it, Edith.
I got no appetite anymore.
Somebody get me a cigar.

05:55.387 --> 05:57.322
Right away.
No.
Let me, ma.

05:58.824 --> 06:00.992
Did he bring
these vitamins with him?

06:01.060 --> 06:04.762
Oh, no. When I went shopping
they was on his food order.

06:04.830 --> 06:08.232
His-- his food order?

06:08.300 --> 06:10.868
Edith, these vitamins
cost the moon.

06:10.936 --> 06:14.939
- What else
was on the food order?
- Nothing. Just the regular.

06:15.007 --> 06:17.308
Meat, fruit, liquor.

06:17.376 --> 06:20.011
You bought him liquor?

06:20.079 --> 06:24.282
You only had rye.
He wanted Brandy.

06:24.350 --> 06:28.353
He wanted Brandy?
Daddy, I don't see
any cigars here.

06:28.420 --> 06:32.390
Well, just look a little harder,
little girl, will ya?
Use your eyes over there.

06:32.458 --> 06:34.392
Edith, what have we got
going here? Brandy?

06:34.460 --> 06:37.295
Who do I look like,
the Duke of windsor?

06:37.363 --> 06:39.563
Edith, let me see
the rest of the food order.

06:39.631 --> 06:43.667
I don't have it.
I think I threw it away.

06:43.735 --> 06:46.070
What do you mean
you think you threw it away?

06:46.138 --> 06:49.240
"A," you did or "b," you didn't.
Pick one.

06:49.308 --> 06:52.710
I think I'll pick "a."

06:54.713 --> 06:57.382
Daddy, there aren't
any cigars here.

06:57.449 --> 07:00.018
She says there are
no cigars there.
What happened to my cigars?

07:00.085 --> 07:03.087
I guess you better
ask Oscar.

07:03.155 --> 07:05.823
Oscar don't smoke cigars.
He does now.

07:05.891 --> 07:09.227
Well, now, that does it!
Now that's the thing
that broke the straw.

07:09.294 --> 07:13.431
That's all there is to it.
I'm going to get rid of that
freeloader today. Right now.

07:13.499 --> 07:16.667
<i>Mike, go up and tell him.</i>

07:16.735 --> 07:19.570
- Why me?
- Because I asked you to.

07:19.638 --> 07:21.906
Can't you do that?
Run upstairs, huh?

07:21.973 --> 07:26.477
Tell him get out of bed,
get out of my pajamas
and get his tail down here.

07:26.545 --> 07:28.979
And youse two, come on
and clear off the table.
Come on.

07:29.048 --> 07:32.917
Maybe we'd better wait.
What for, Edith?

07:32.984 --> 07:36.754
It's almost his lunchtime,
and his steak
is already defrosting.

07:36.821 --> 07:40.558
His steak?
Edith, put that steak
back in the freezer.

07:40.625 --> 07:44.462
It's probably big enough
for the four of us. We can
have it for new year's Eve.

07:44.530 --> 07:47.532
He ain't gonna have time for
no lunch, 'cause I'm gonna
get rid of Oscar...

07:47.599 --> 07:50.301
In post and in haste.

07:50.369 --> 07:54.205
Come on. Get the food
off the table. He'll eat
anything in sight, that guy.

07:54.273 --> 07:56.941
Hurry up.
Come on, Gloria.

07:57.008 --> 07:59.843
I tell you something,
family can go just so far.

07:59.911 --> 08:02.746
Then you gotta grab
the bull by the "corns"
and heave-ho.

08:06.351 --> 08:09.187
[ Clears throat ]
Did you get him up?
Is he coming down here?

08:09.254 --> 08:11.755
No.
What do you mean, no?

08:11.823 --> 08:13.924
You didn't get him up,
or he ain't coming down?

08:15.327 --> 08:19.663
Both.
What is that foolish look
on your face?

08:19.731 --> 08:21.732
Why didn't you
wake Oscar up?

08:21.800 --> 08:24.502
He's dead.

08:24.570 --> 08:26.870
What?

08:26.938 --> 08:29.006
He's dead.

08:30.209 --> 08:33.644
What are you telling me
a thing like that for?

08:33.712 --> 08:35.813
'Cause he is.

08:35.880 --> 08:38.381
No.

08:38.450 --> 08:40.884
Yeah.

08:40.952 --> 08:43.121
No.

08:45.257 --> 08:48.058
Yeah.

08:48.127 --> 08:50.060
Wait.

09:08.947 --> 09:11.949
Well, he sat
on my face again.

09:13.918 --> 09:19.023
He's got relations in 16 cities,
but he's got to pick
my attic to die in.

09:19.090 --> 09:21.592
Is Oscar down yet, Archie?

09:21.660 --> 09:23.827
Uh, no, he ain't, Edith.
Say nothing to
your mother-in-law.

09:23.895 --> 09:26.197
She can't handle these things.
She flies all to pieces.

09:26.265 --> 09:28.966
Is something wrong?
What happened?

09:29.034 --> 09:30.734
Nothing's wrong.
Nothing's wrong.

09:30.802 --> 09:33.371
[ Softly ] She flies
right to pieces. Keep quiet.
Where's Oscar?

09:33.438 --> 09:35.939
Uh, in bed.
He hasn't moved.

09:38.777 --> 09:43.113
What's everybody
acting so funny about?
Is something wrong with Oscar?

09:43.182 --> 09:46.116
She's going right to pieces,
nobody even told her yet.
Shh!

09:46.185 --> 09:48.186
Told me what?
Is it about Oscar?
Told her what?

09:48.253 --> 09:50.588
Edith, please.
Don't get hysterical.

09:50.656 --> 09:52.823
I think there's something
wrong with Oscar.

09:52.891 --> 09:55.059
Now, don't go up there.
Why not?
Calm down now,

09:55.126 --> 09:57.428
you two women,
just calm down!

09:57.496 --> 10:00.565
Gee whiz. There's no reason
to get hysterical
at a time like this.

10:00.632 --> 10:02.633
What we don't need is
a lot of screaming and crying!

10:02.701 --> 10:04.635
Who's screaming?
Who's crying?
Just calm down.

10:04.703 --> 10:07.805
Michael,
what do you mean?
Relax. Take it easy.

10:07.872 --> 10:11.942
The two of youse
just dummy up, huh?

10:12.010 --> 10:16.480
Now let me handle this.
Edith, uh,

10:16.548 --> 10:21.385
I got something
to tell ya.
Oscar's dead, isn't he?

10:27.058 --> 10:30.894
Why couldn't you wait
for me to tell you that?

10:30.962 --> 10:34.565
Ma! Ma!
What'll we do?
[ Crying ]

10:34.633 --> 10:38.636
Why, we'll call the doctor.

10:38.704 --> 10:42.306
We'll call Dr. Kelly
so he can come over here...

10:42.374 --> 10:45.610
And sign the certificate
so we can move the body.

10:45.677 --> 10:48.212
- <i>[ Phone rings ]</i>
<i>- [ Screams ]</i>

10:48.280 --> 10:51.449
Let me through here.
I'll move the body.

10:53.619 --> 10:57.455
Hello? Yes, operator.
Put him on, will ya?

10:57.522 --> 10:59.590
It's Lou from Detroit.

10:59.658 --> 11:04.495
Hello, Lou.
Hi. Archie from New York.

11:04.563 --> 11:07.398
Yeah.
[ Chuckles ]

11:07.466 --> 11:10.134
Lou, I was calling you
for something before,

11:10.201 --> 11:13.070
but now it's something else
I gotta tell ya.

11:13.138 --> 11:16.974
A-anyway, uh, get ready
for a little bad news.

11:17.041 --> 11:19.377
Uh, cousin Oscar's dead here.

11:21.546 --> 11:25.883
What do you mean,
"how's the weather
in New York?"

11:25.950 --> 11:30.621
I just told you Oscar's dead.
We gotta get him back
to Detroit to be buried.

11:30.689 --> 11:33.190
Now-now, come on, Lou.

11:33.258 --> 11:37.094
Now you know how he was
closest to your end of
the family out there.

11:37.162 --> 11:40.164
I think you're legally
responsible for the body.

11:40.231 --> 11:42.600
What do you mean possession
is nine-tenths of the law?

11:42.668 --> 11:47.171
Come on.

11:47.238 --> 11:49.440
[ Stammering ]
Listen, Lou.
All right, don't get mad.

11:49.508 --> 11:52.843
We can do it here.
He can be buried in New York.
Edith and I can handle it.

11:52.911 --> 11:55.413
But what about the money?

11:55.480 --> 11:58.982
Well, you got plenty
of relations out there.
Pass the hat. Get something.

11:59.050 --> 12:01.619
Send us the money.
Wire it to me.

12:01.687 --> 12:06.324
You do that, Lou.
Get back to me and fast, huh?
Good-bye.

12:06.391 --> 12:09.059
You crumb.

12:09.127 --> 12:13.297
How much is a house call
from doc Kelly?
$20.

12:13.365 --> 12:16.701
And how much do you figure
that phone to Detroit?
About 3 1/2.

12:16.768 --> 12:21.405
Oh, geez.
And maybe another 30
to have this guy collected.

12:21.473 --> 12:24.308
You're still doing it
to me, Oscar, boy.

12:24.376 --> 12:28.979
You ain't dead 20 minutes
and already you cost me
more than 50 bucks.

12:33.719 --> 12:36.053
<i>What's that, Freddy?</i>
<i>Look-look, Freddy.</i>

12:36.120 --> 12:38.188
I mean, I'm only
a second cousin,
you're a first.

12:38.256 --> 12:41.459
Now you gotta help
with this thing.
I did call other people.

12:41.526 --> 12:45.363
I called cousin Lou in Detroit.
He's taking up a collection
of most of the relations there.

12:45.430 --> 12:48.265
But, listen, you gotta
help me with this thing too.

12:48.333 --> 12:53.003
Well, Fred, just do what
you can and get back to me, huh?
Fast. I'll wait for the call.

12:53.071 --> 12:57.241
Yeah. Good-bye.
You crumb.

12:57.308 --> 13:01.645
What do you got to show us?
Like I was telling your wife,
you made a wise choice.

13:01.713 --> 13:04.214
By entrusting your beloved
to a neighborhood mortuary,

13:04.282 --> 13:09.152
you're gonna come out
smelling like a rose.
Whitehead, how much?

13:09.220 --> 13:12.390
First and foremost,
whitehead brothers wants to
create a beautiful...

13:12.457 --> 13:15.092
And lasting memory picture
of the loved one.

13:15.159 --> 13:17.495
Oh, ain't that nice.

13:19.898 --> 13:24.769
Undertakers sound like
mother's day cards.

13:24.836 --> 13:28.171
Uh, Mrs. bunker, we say
funeral directors now.

13:28.239 --> 13:30.608
You're not supposed
to say undertakers anymore.

13:30.675 --> 13:34.712
Oh. Like the mafia.
<i>[ Archie ]</i>
<i>Now stifle yourself.</i>

13:36.882 --> 13:38.816
Whitehead, come here.

13:38.884 --> 13:43.554
Now listen,
I know you 13 years
from the lodge, right?

13:43.622 --> 13:47.458
And you know me.
Now, can I get a simple answer
to a simple question? How much?

13:47.526 --> 13:49.660
Well, let's take a look
at the book.
Go ahead.

13:49.728 --> 13:54.231
All right, here's--
we got 329-l, arch.
We call it the patriot.

13:54.299 --> 13:57.301
Now the motif is early American,
as you can see.

13:57.368 --> 14:00.538
Maple hardwood.
Red, white and blue quilting.

14:00.605 --> 14:05.108
And painted on the inside lid,
facing the deceased,
the American flag.

14:07.813 --> 14:10.147
How much?
What's the difference
how much, Archie?

14:10.214 --> 14:13.818
Mr. whitehead, I've been
listening in, and if you
don't mind my speaking openly--

14:13.885 --> 14:16.887
what better time for it, son?
In the presence of death,

14:16.955 --> 14:21.459
we are all of us achingly aware
of the solitude--
whitehead, hold it, will ya?

14:21.526 --> 14:26.296
Spare us
the stained-glass language.
What was you saying?

14:26.364 --> 14:29.600
I just think
this whole thing is barbaric.
It's like some kind of circus.

14:29.668 --> 14:33.671
You said it.
And I'm the clown
in the middle ring.

14:33.738 --> 14:37.575
Come on, whitehead.
Now how much are you going to
charge me for that flag number?

14:37.642 --> 14:41.645
$325.
$325 just for a box?

14:41.713 --> 14:44.748
The casket, Archie.
His home through eternity.

14:44.816 --> 14:47.551
The man couldn't care less
about a home when he was living.

14:47.619 --> 14:50.454
I'm supposed to give him
a home through eternity?

14:50.522 --> 14:53.190
[ Doorbell ringing ]
Hold on now.

14:53.257 --> 14:55.593
No. Edith, Edith.
No, no. I'll answer the door.

14:55.660 --> 14:57.561
I can't stand
looking at them things.

14:57.629 --> 15:01.131
Will you go over
and pick something out, huh?
From the back of the book.

15:04.002 --> 15:05.936
Oh, Mrs. Jefferson.
How are you?

15:06.004 --> 15:10.508
Mr. bunker, I came
as soon as I heard the news.
I'm so sorry.

15:10.575 --> 15:13.677
What are you gonna do?
Was his death untimely?

15:13.745 --> 15:16.246
Yeah, around lunchtime.

15:21.920 --> 15:26.289
Well, I brought this for you.
Thank you. Well, you know
where the table is over there.

15:26.357 --> 15:30.160
Hey, Edith,
Mrs. Jefferson is here.
What a lovely cake.

15:30.228 --> 15:33.063
- Edith, a moment over here.
A moment.
- [ Doorbell ringing ]

15:33.131 --> 15:35.799
All right. Edith, we got
people coming.

15:35.867 --> 15:39.537
Try and get an apron on her,
maybe they'll think
she's the maid.

15:39.604 --> 15:43.106
Oh, Archie.
Don't argue.
Go on.

15:46.244 --> 15:51.248
Oh, hiya, Jimmy.
Yeah, yeah, yeah. I know.
Archie, Archie, Archie.

15:51.315 --> 15:53.717
Don't say nothing.
I know how you feel.

15:53.785 --> 15:58.789
We know just how you feel.
Jim lost his father
three years ago last month.

15:58.857 --> 16:03.727
It was a beautiful service.
926 bucks.

16:03.795 --> 16:07.965
Uh, excuse me, Jimmy, huh?
Edith, the mcnabs are here.

16:08.033 --> 16:10.868
Whitehead, come here.
Let me ask you something.

16:10.936 --> 16:14.438
Did you do the job
on Jim mcnab's old man
about two years ago?

16:14.505 --> 16:18.475
Jim mcnab's father.
$926.

16:18.543 --> 16:21.011
We did it.

16:21.079 --> 16:25.015
Are you telling me that
mcnab laid out that much
for a funeral, huh?

16:25.083 --> 16:27.985
<i>[ Doorbell ringing ]</i>
<i>The important thing is when you</i>
<i>walk away from that cemetery...</i>

16:28.053 --> 16:32.289
After a whitehead funeral,
you're going to be able
to hold your head up high.

16:32.356 --> 16:35.525
Whitehead--
Archie, it's a telegram
for you.

16:35.594 --> 16:38.762
Good. It's the relations
in Detroit with the collection.

16:38.830 --> 16:41.331
Let's see how high they want
to hold up their heads.

16:43.835 --> 16:47.170
About this high.
Read it.

16:48.940 --> 16:52.843
Seventy-three dollars
and twenty-five cents.

16:52.911 --> 16:56.313
Our pet department
gets that for a canary.

16:56.380 --> 16:59.449
Excuse me.

16:59.517 --> 17:02.519
Whitehead, it's time
for a little plain talk.

17:02.587 --> 17:05.923
Can a guy buy something,
such as used?

17:14.633 --> 17:16.967
Used?
Used.

17:18.368 --> 17:22.640
Any floor models,
demonstrators, fleet jobs?
Whatever.

17:24.643 --> 17:27.210
What you want then
is something modestly priced.

17:27.278 --> 17:30.981
Cheap, whitehead.
Dirt cheap.

17:31.049 --> 17:33.517
<i>[ Doorbell ringing ]</i>
<i>Now find something</i>
<i>like that for me in here.</i>

17:33.584 --> 17:36.920
I gotta make a phone call.

17:36.988 --> 17:40.257
Oh, Edith.
[ Sobbing ]
Where's Archie?

17:40.324 --> 17:43.861
[ Sobbing ]
Archie.

17:43.928 --> 17:46.596
I-I came
as soon as I heard.

17:46.665 --> 17:50.500
Who even knew Oscar
was living with you,
the poor love.

17:50.568 --> 17:54.672
Did he suffer long?
Was it terrible?

17:58.342 --> 18:00.678
Who are you?

18:08.853 --> 18:12.156
[ Crying continues ]
I'm cousin Bertha.

18:12.223 --> 18:16.060
Wilber's daughter
from ozone park.
Hey, Edith.

18:16.127 --> 18:21.565
It's been eleven years.
I'll pull myself together.
We'll have a long talk.

18:21.632 --> 18:25.635
Geez, a death in the family,
they come fallin'
out of the woodwork.

18:25.704 --> 18:29.372
Mr. bunker,
do you think the funeral
will be in the morning?

18:29.440 --> 18:31.408
I usually do my shopping
in the morning.

18:31.475 --> 18:35.713
Well, I'll keep it in mind.
Maybe we can pass
the market on the way.

18:40.318 --> 18:44.188
Hello.
Come on, operator, will ya?

18:44.255 --> 18:48.258
Listen, I'm trying
to get a line through
to Cicero, Illinois.

18:48.326 --> 18:53.496
Yeah. Wh-what are you doing?
Well, nuts to you too!

18:53.564 --> 18:56.934
Mike, come over here.
Stop feeding your face
and help me, will ya?

18:57.001 --> 18:59.002
<i>Do something around here.</i>
<i>What do you want?</i>

18:59.070 --> 19:02.072
Keep dialing that number
on the pad there. When you
get a line, let me know.

19:02.140 --> 19:05.142
<i>H-hey, Archie.</i>
<i>Billy hartfeld,</i>
<i>how'd you find out?</i>

19:05.210 --> 19:07.845
Oh, Kenny's wife
told my old lady.

19:07.912 --> 19:11.181
Anyway, when's the funeral?
I don't know, Billy.
We're working up to it.

19:11.249 --> 19:13.217
[ Doorbell ringing ]
Well, whenever.
Don't worry.

19:13.284 --> 19:15.252
I mean, the whole department
is going to turn out.

19:15.319 --> 19:18.488
We got in
the new union contract.
Half-day for funerals.

19:18.556 --> 19:22.926
Oh, come on.
Find a chair somewheres
and sit down, huh?

19:22.994 --> 19:27.998
- It's the reverend felcher.
- Good night, nurse.
Hold it, whitehead.

19:28.066 --> 19:30.167
Hi there, reverend.
How are you?

19:30.235 --> 19:33.904
Mr. bunker,
I was so unhappy
to hear of your sorrow.

19:33.972 --> 19:37.007
I know that mere words
cannot substitute for your loss.

19:37.075 --> 19:40.577
Well, you can say
that again, reverend.

19:40.645 --> 19:44.481
You gotta excuse me 'cause
I got my "funereal" director
over here.

19:44.548 --> 19:48.051
So, uh, er, just do something.
Eat some cake and cookies.

19:48.119 --> 19:50.287
Go ahead, whitehead.
Shoot.

19:50.354 --> 19:53.356
I got an item here
on page eight.
Now, it's the lowest one we got.

19:53.424 --> 19:58.262
Number 101-p, $97.50.
But there's no guarantee
against warping.
Sold.

19:58.329 --> 20:00.664
All right. Let's see
what it comes to
with the other essentials.

20:00.731 --> 20:04.067
There's the burial plot,
memorial tablet,
limousine service,

20:04.135 --> 20:06.703
memorial prayer booklets,
you're building it up,
whitehead.

20:06.771 --> 20:09.339
Recorded organ music,
which I'll throw in free.
You're building up.

20:09.407 --> 20:12.575
Give me the numbers.
All right.
It's about that figure there.

20:12.643 --> 20:16.313
That's over 600 bucks.
Whitehead, I can't go for that.
We can talk it down--

20:16.380 --> 20:18.015
arch.
It's ringing.
<i>Huh?</i>

20:18.082 --> 20:20.417
Don't go away.
I got a call.

20:22.520 --> 20:26.356
Yeah. Hello,
is that you, Freddy?
Well, who's this?

20:26.424 --> 20:29.592
Oh, Debbie Marie, huh?
Well, is your daddy there?

20:31.062 --> 20:33.897
It's your birthday?

20:33.965 --> 20:36.800
No, no, Debbie Marie,
I don't want to guess
how old you are.

20:40.338 --> 20:45.843
All right, five.
Six, then.

20:45.910 --> 20:47.878
Look, kid,
this is a long-distance call.

20:47.946 --> 20:52.449
I don't give a damn
how old you are.
Get your old man on the phone!

20:52.516 --> 20:56.686
Freddy. Freddy, where are ya?
I'm waitin' for your call here.

20:56.754 --> 20:59.422
Huh? I know it's
Debbie Marie's birthday.

20:59.490 --> 21:01.658
I don't want to guess her age.
I done that already.

21:01.726 --> 21:03.894
Freddy, are you gonna
help me or not?

21:05.330 --> 21:08.165
What-what do you mean
your wife won't let you?

21:08.233 --> 21:11.134
No, no. Let them
cut the cake themselves.
Stay with me on this line.

21:11.202 --> 21:14.204
I called you long distance.
Freddy? Freddy, now don't
get off the line.

21:14.272 --> 21:16.506
Fred? Fred?
There he goes.

21:16.574 --> 21:19.576
What a crumb.
Get outta the way, will ya?

21:19.643 --> 21:22.012
Hey, Archie?
Let me talk to you
for a second.
What?

21:22.080 --> 21:24.748
I think I figured
something out here. I've been
doing some checking up.

21:24.815 --> 21:28.485
I figured out a way it won't
cost you a penny.
If you want to go for it.

21:28.552 --> 21:30.687
I'll go for anything
like that. What is it?

21:30.755 --> 21:33.757
You see, a cousin is not like
a brother or a sister.

21:33.824 --> 21:36.493
I mean, there may be
a moral obligation,
but there's no legal one.

21:36.560 --> 21:38.896
All you have to do
is call the coroner's office,

21:38.963 --> 21:41.498
they'll go to whitehead's,
pick up the body
and dispose of it.

21:41.565 --> 21:46.003
Wait a minute. Wait a minute.
I already sent him to makeup.
We'll pay for the makeup.

21:46.070 --> 21:48.005
Will they pay
for the funeral?

21:48.072 --> 21:50.073
Well, that's just it.
There is no funeral.

21:50.141 --> 21:53.143
They just put him
in the ground in a place
they call Potter's field.

21:53.211 --> 21:55.145
You know,
it's for paupers.
Well, that's Oscar.

21:55.213 --> 21:58.448
Hey, boy. Hey, in a pinch
you really come through there.
That's sensational.

21:58.516 --> 22:02.319
Hey. I hate to do this
to you, whitehead, but we're
gonna go this way for nothing.

22:02.387 --> 22:07.391
Archie, the reverend felcher
would like you to tell him
something about Oscar.

22:07.458 --> 22:11.594
You know, for the service
at the funeral.
There ain't gonna be no funeral.

22:11.662 --> 22:14.664
What?
Don't argue. Whitehead,
you heard what I said.

22:14.732 --> 22:18.402
Put your folders away.
I heard you, Archie. But your
friends and relatives didn't.

22:18.469 --> 22:21.805
I'm waitin' to hear you
tell them.
You're gonna hear me right now.

22:21.872 --> 22:24.874
No, Edith.
I'm not gonna do it.
You gotta have a funeral.

22:24.943 --> 22:28.245
Uh, listen, everybody.
Give me your attention,
all of youse, huh?

22:28.313 --> 22:31.181
I wanna tell you
something about the funeral.

22:31.249 --> 22:35.252
Archie, listen. Don't you see?
Funerals ain't for the dead.

22:35.320 --> 22:38.322
They're for the living.
All right, maybe you
didn't like Oscar.

22:38.389 --> 22:43.393
But he don't matter now.
What matters now
is your friends, your relatives,

22:43.461 --> 22:47.130
the man upstairs,
the maker of us all.

22:47.198 --> 22:50.167
That matters, arch.
That matters.
Oh, whitehead--

22:50.234 --> 22:54.871
Archie, we've been through
worse than this.
When was that, Edith?

22:58.009 --> 23:02.712
Well, we've been through
things just as bad.
When, Edith?

23:02.780 --> 23:06.549
Well, then we've been
pretty lucky, ain't we?

23:08.386 --> 23:11.721
What do you want me to do?
Spend over $600 on a funeral...

23:11.789 --> 23:15.892
For a cousin
who used to sit on my face?

23:17.261 --> 23:19.762
He'll never do it again.

23:25.503 --> 23:29.406
[ Clears throat ]
Now, folks, what I
want to tell you is, uh--

23:49.727 --> 23:53.063
uh, the funeral, uh,
is gonna be Saturday.
Archie?

23:53.131 --> 23:55.798
What?
You better make it Friday.
They're negotiating right now,

23:55.866 --> 23:58.135
but the grave diggers might
go on strike Friday midnight.

23:58.202 --> 24:02.705
Friday, everybody.
The funeral's
going to be on Friday.

24:15.153 --> 24:17.987
Well, thank heavens
that's over with.

24:18.056 --> 24:20.023
Boy,
what a travesty.

24:20.091 --> 24:23.093
It was nice, wasn't it?

24:25.696 --> 24:30.700
I thought
the reverend felcher's remarks
were so beautiful.

24:30.768 --> 24:35.439
Looking back
over their childhood,
Oscar's and Archie's.

24:35.506 --> 24:39.042
How they played together
all those years--

24:39.110 --> 24:41.144
what do you mean,
"how they played together"?

24:41.212 --> 24:43.813
All Oscar ever did
was knock Archie down
and sit on his face.

24:43.881 --> 24:46.383
Hold it, huh?

24:46.451 --> 24:50.787
The deceased
ain't hardly cold yet.
Have a little respect.

24:50.854 --> 24:55.192
Sheesh. What's with him?
Before the funeral,
he was another man.

24:55.259 --> 24:59.762
I must say,
it was impressive.
Barbaric, but impressive.

24:59.830 --> 25:04.801
Where'd those people come from?
What made so many
people show up?

25:04.868 --> 25:08.538
Are you kidding?
When Archie bunker
gives a funeral...

25:13.344 --> 25:15.945
People show up.

25:35.833 --> 25:40.237
[ Announcer ]
All in family <i>was recorded</i>
<i>on tape before a live audience.</i>

